<div class="actioncontent">

	<div class="formRow">
		<label for="Subject">Subject:</label>
		<input id="Subject" type="text" class="wide" name="Subject" size="45" value="Support Strong Gainful Employment Regulations"/>
	</div>

	<div class="formRow">
		<div id="Content_div" class="letterContent">
			<label for="Content">Your Letter:</label>
			<textarea name="Content" id="Content" rows="15" cols="45">Dear Representative,

As your constituent, I am writing to strongly urge you to support the U.S. Department of Education’s efforts to finalize strong gainful employment regulations.
 
It is certainly true that some for-profit colleges do provide a service of value to their students, but far too many employ deceptive recruitment practices to lure students into enrolling (particularly low-income students and veterans) to receive their federal financial aid. These students then receive none of the valuable career skills for which they enrolled in the program and they leave with enormous amounts of debt. Subsequently, they can’t find a job, they default on their loans, and taxpayers’ dollars are wasted in the process, all while these companies continue to profit off of student loan debt and federal financial aid.
 
Some for-profit colleges receive nearly 90 percent or more of their total funds from federal taxpayers. Moreover, for-profit colleges enroll only about 11 percent of all U.S. college students, but account for nearly half of all student loan defaults.

Limiting access to programs that don't graduate students with useful workforce skills does not harm students; it protects students against dangerous programs.
 
Students deserve a strong rule that will truly hold career education programs accountable for providing them with a high-quality education, one that prepares them for a career with a family-supporting wage. 
  
At a time when the federal budget is tight and student debt has already surpassed $1 trillion, strong gainful employment regulations will help to ensure that we are spending each tax dollar wisely.
 
Thank you,</textarea>
		</div>
	</div>

</div>

	</div>
	
	



